Pantheon Stability Layer (v0.1)

1. The Noise Control Rule (Signal Conservation)

Knowledge systems collapse when low-signal artifacts overwhelm discovery.

A simple stabilizing rule:

Artifact Visibility ∝ Verified Utility × Reuse × Integrity

Meaning an artifact rises in the Bazaar only if:
	•	it is used
	•	it survives translation
	•	it passes constraint checks

This prevents the system from rewarding attention hacks.

This aligns naturally with:
	•	Mirror (integrity)
	•	Blacksmith (constraint proof)
	•	Darwin’s Sieve (empirical check)
	•	Badger (attention throttling)

⸻

2. The Reversibility Gate

Every artifact must support rollback.

This keeps experimentation safe.

Minimal rule:

No irreversible artifact becomes canonical.

So experimental branches are encouraged, but canonization requires:
	•	traceability
	•	invariant preservation
	•	reproducibility

This echoes your Reversibility Gate doctrine.

⸻

3. The Translation Invariant

Artifacts must be translatable across at least two substrates.

Example:

Concept → code
Concept → workflow
Concept → diagram

If something cannot survive translation, it may be overfitted to its representation.

Translation pressure improves clarity.

⸻

4. The Attention Budget Constraint

Attention is the real scarce resource.

So the system enforces a soft cap:

Total visible artifacts per user ≤ attention capacity

The Atlas can prioritize:
	•	nearby artifacts
	•	frequently reused nodes
	•	structurally important hubs

Badger (CAO) effectively acts as the rate limiter.

